This project aims to assess how the East Antarctic Ice Sheet responds to periods of warm climate by reconstructing ice sheet behaviour during warm periods in the geologic past. This is important because assessing the sensitivity of Earth's largest ice sheet is a key objective for climate change adaptation and mitigation, and the East Antarctic Ice Sheet (EAIS) represents the greatest potential source of future sea level rise.

The primary scientific outcome of this project is a geologic record of ice sheet fluctuations (thickening and thinning) that spans the last ~15 million years. The record is built on relict glacial deposits at two sites in the central Transantarctic Mountains - Roberts Massif and Otway Massif - adjacent to the center of the ice sheet, and is dated with multiple types of cosmogenic surface-exposure methods. Overall, this new record reveals how the surface of the EAIS in this central region has changed over time. Relative to the modern landscape, our findings show that the ice sheet surface was slightly higher during earlier parts of our record (e.g., the warm Miocene) and has lowered gradually over ~15 million years. The most striking aspect of the record, however, is that is shows the EAIS has remained largely unchanged for a very long period. Focusing on the Pliocene (5-2.6 million years ago), parts of which are thought to be analogous to modern global warming, our record suggests the ice sheet was generally present during that time but that there is a conspicuous gap during the middle Pliocene. Whether or not that gap indicates the EAIS shrank due to climate warming has key implications for our understanding of ice sheet stability and will be tested with additional geologic investigations on the continent. 

As the coldest and driest continent on Earth, Antarctica is well known for low rates of weathering and erosion. Through our use of multiple cosmogenic nuclides, a second scientific outcome of this project is quantification of the long-term erosion rate for the central Transantarctic Mountains, which we has established as &lt; 5 cm/million years. This is important information for future research into the geology, glaciology, and climate of Antarctica. 

The glacial-geologic record for Roberts Massif, including geomorphic maps, cosmogenic ages, weathering rate calculations, and a discussion of the record's scientific implications, was published (August 2020) in the open-access journal The Cryosphere (https://tc.copernicus.org/articles/14/2647/2020/tc-14-2647-2020-discussion.html). A second paper, documenting the glacial-geologic record from Otway Massif, is currently in progress and will be submitted for open-access publication in 2021. All geochronologic data produced are available via the ICE-D: ANTARCTICA online database, for free use and re-evaluation by public/scientific users. Project findings have also been presented at three international conferences.

Complementing the scientific deliverables, this project fulfilled its commitment to the education of students and training of the next generation of scientists. Specifically, one undergraduate participated in fieldwork during the 2015-16 Antarctic season, after which she traveled to Berkeley Geochronology Center to assist with the measurement of geochronology samples. These experiences formed the basis for her undergraduate thesis at UMaine. One graduate student participated in fieldwork during the 2016-17 Antarctic season and was trained in the preparation and measurement of cosmogenic geochronology samples. The student took the lead in preparing the project?s first paper for publication (of which she is lead author), and is now pursuing a PhD in geochemistry. The project also enabled a second graduate student to receive training in Antarctic fieldwork and glacial geology. This student (since awarded a Marie Sklodowska-Curie Actions postdoctoral fellowship) took responsibility for constructing the young end of our Roberts Massif record, which we anticipate will be published in 2021. 

From the outset, project findings have been incorporated into undergraduate curricula both at UMaine and Dartmouth College. Project team members have delivered distilled age-appropriate versions of findings and research experiences to K-12 audiences, including elementary/middle schools in Maine and high schools in Massachusetts, and also via the Skype-a-Scientist initiative. Beyond the classroom, the PI has included artwork and photography stemming from project fieldwork in three art exhibitions since 2017, including two in Maine and one in Ireland, with the overarching objective of bringing publicly funded science to a public audience via art. All three have been well received and were used widely by elementary schools to introduce the rationale for science.  

The project has delivered:

A 15 million-year geologic record of EAIS fluctuations in the central Transantarctic Mountains, including maps and chronologic data;
Constraint on long-term Antarctic weathering rates; 
One open-access publication to date (two more anticipated in 2021) and full online storage of data;
Training of one female undergraduate and two female graduate students in field-based geology;
Interactive dissemination of findings and experiences to K-12 and university students;
Public exhibitions of science-inspired art.




